# get distance in kilometers via longitude and latitude

def haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2, to_radians=True, earth_radius=6371):
    if to_radians:
        lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = np.radians([lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])

    a = np.sin((lat2-lat1)/2.0)**2 + \
        np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin((lon2-lon1)/2.0)**2

    return earth_radius * 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))


bike['dist'] = haversine(bike['start_station_latitude'], bike['start_station_longitude'],bike['end_station_latitude']
                       , bike['end_station_longitude'])

In [17]:
# get time of day
c = []
for i in bike['start_time'].astype(str).str[10:]:
    if int(i.split(':')[0]) >= 0 and int(i.split(':')[0]) < 6 :
        c.append('night')
    elif int(i.split(':')[0]) >= 6 and int(i.split(':')[0]) < 12:
        c.append('morning')
    elif int(i.split(':')[0]) >= 12 and  int(i.split(':')[0]) < 18:
        c.append('afternoon')
    elif int(i.split(':')[0]) >= 18 and int(i.split(':')[0]) < 23:
        c.append('evening')
    else:
        c.append('night')
        
bike['time_of_day'] = c

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest are :

  • What days of the week , time of day , month were most trips taken?
  • What gender, age groups and user_type are associated with the trip?
  • Distance and speed distributions and the relationships between these features.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Features such as duration_sec , start_day_of_week , time_of_day, month , dist, speed,age, and gender.

# function to add percentage labels to plot
def perc(type_counts , sum_value):
    for i in range(type_counts.shape[0]):
        count = type_counts[i]
        perct_str = '{:0.1f}'.format(count*100/ sum_value)
        plt.text(i, count +700, perct_str + '%', ha = 'center')
        sb.despine(left=True)
        plt.yticks(())
        plt.ylabel('');

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most riders began their journey on between Tuesdays,Wednesday and Thursday mostly in the aftertoon time. Most of the riders were subscribers , of male gender and of age 30 -35 , covering a distance of about 2km , with speeds up to 10km/hr.

There aren't unusal points so far in the analysis and I didnt need to perform any transformations.(shape from transformation is the same as normal plot shape).

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Some of the columns are featured engineered from other variables in the dataset. All of the feature engineering and cleaning were done in the Preliminary Wrangling Section.

I made use of the latitude and longitude points to calculate the distance travelled between stations.

I used the newly created distance (dist) and duration_sec column to get the approximate speed of the riders duration the journey.

I created an age column using the member_birth_year column by subtracting the the year from 2018.

The start_day_of_week, time_of_day, and month columns were created to get month, time of day and the day of the week the trips began.

No unusual distributions

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The investigation shows that most male riders That started their trip in the month of October covered a larger distance than riders in other months, although most of these riders(in the month of October) didn't cover more than 2km.

Most subscribers were males and covered a larger distance than the customers.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I expected the correlation between speed and age to be negative but this might be due to some outliers in the dataset.

Conclusions¶

  • Most trips started on Tuesday and in the month of October in the afternoon.

  • Most of the riders were males (73.5%) and females (24.9%).

  • Most riders were between the ages of 25-35 years.

  • Most trips were between 1 -2 km

  • Male riders covered more distance than other genders. (72%)

  • Subscribers had the highest total distance covered and time taken, 84% and 70% respectively.

  • Mean speed of riders was approximately 10km/hr.

  • Male riders had the highest mean speed of about 10km /hr , followed by the other (about 9.9km/hr) and then females (9.2km/hr)

  • The elderly (70 -140 years) took longer time to complete their journey.
